Supplementary materials

Forrest W. Crawford

Supplement: how many people inject drugs?

Problem

Question: How many people inject drugs (e.g. opioids) in my city?

Data: counts of \(m\) individuals’ emergency room visits for overdose, \(X_1,\ldots,X_m\), all positive, for one unit of time (e.g. year). We only see \(X_i\) if person \(i\) had at least one overdose.

Setup

Let \(N\) be the number of people who inject drugs in the city.

Let \(X_1,\ldots,X_N\) be the number of times (possibly zero) each has overdosed and been taken to the emergency room, in one year.

Let \(M=m\) the number who have had at least one overdose. We know \(X_1,\ldots,X_m > 0\)

Assumptions and their consequences

Two substantive assumptions:

  1. Everyone who has had at least one overdose went to the emergency room.
  2. Every drug injector has an overdose (independently of others) with constant rate \(\lambda\) per year.

Then each drug injector’s overdose pattern is a Poisson process with rate \(\lambda\). Since the unit of time is \(t=1\) year, the number of overdoses person \(i\) has in one year is distributed as

\[ X_i \sim \text{Poisson}(\lambda) \]

so

\[ \Pr(X_i=x) = \frac{\lambda^x e^{-\lambda}}{x!} \]

However, the hospital records only have \(X_i\) when \(X_i>0\). We can compute this (conditional) distribution. Recall that

\[ \Pr(X_i=0) = e^{-\lambda} \]

so \(\Pr(X_i>0) = 1-e^{-\lambda}\)$ and by Bayes’ Theorem \[ \Pr(X_i=x|X_i>0) = \frac{\lambda^x e^{-\lambda}}{x!(1-e^{-\lambda})} \]

Since we can write the distribution of the observed data \(X_1,\ldots,X_m\) in terms of \(\lambda\), we can estimate \(\lambda\) from the observed data.

Estimating \(\lambda\)

The likelihood of \(X_1,\ldots,X_m\) is the joint probability of these data, interpreted as a function of the unknown rate \(\lambda\),

\[ L(\lambda) = \prod_{i=1}^m \frac{\lambda^{x_i} e^{-\lambda}}{x_i!(1-e^{-\lambda})} \]

We wish to maximize \(L(\lambda)\) with respect to \(\lambda\).

The log-likelihood is

\[ \begin{aligned} \ell(\lambda) &\propto \sum_{i=1}^m x_i\log(\lambda) -\lambda - \log(1-e^{-\lambda}) &= \log(\lambda)\left(\sum_{i=1}^m x_i\right) -m\lambda - m\log(1-e^{-\lambda}) \end{aligned} \] We can maximize this function with Newton’s method or any nonlinear optimization algorithm to find \(\hat\lambda\).

Estimating \(N\)

Because \(X_i\) has Poisson distribution, we know \(\Pr(X_i=0) = e^{-\lambda}\) and \(\Pr(X_i>0)=1-e^{-\lambda}\) The number of drug injectors in our records is \(M\), and from this we know

\[ M \sim \text{Binomial}(N,1-e^{-\lambda}) \]

We have an estimate \(\hat\lambda\) of \(\lambda\), and we know that

\[ E[M] = N (1-e^{-\lambda}) \] or \[ M \approx \Pr(X_i>0) \times (\text{number at risk}) \]

Therefore a natural estimator can be formed by substituting the observed value \(M=m\) for \(E[M]\),

\[ m \approx (1-e^{-\hat\lambda}) N . \]

Rearranging, we have the estimate

\[ \hat{N} = \frac{m}{1-e^{-\hat\lambda}} \]

Simulation

Simulate observed data

N_true = 1000
lam_true = 0.7  # overdoses per person per year 
x = rpois(N_true, lam_true)
x_obs = x[x > 0]
m = length(x_obs)

Estimate \(\lambda\)

negloglik = function(lam) {
    -1 * (sum(x_obs) * log(lam) - m * lam - 
        m * log(1 - exp(-lam)))
}
obj = nlm(negloglik, 0.5, stepmax = 0.1)
lam_hat = obj$estimate
obj

Let’s look at the negative log likelihood and our chosen value of \(\hat\lambda\)

lam_seq = seq(0.01, 5, by = 0.01)
plot(lam_seq, negloglik(lam_seq))
abline(v = lam_hat)
text(lam_hat, mean(negloglik(lam_seq)), paste("lam_hat =", 
    round(lam_hat, digits = 2)), pos = 4)

Now estimate \(N\)

N_hat = m/(1 - exp(-lam_hat))
N_hat
## [1] 1042.921

Let’s do this many times and look at the distribution of estimates

nsims = 1000
N_hats = rep(NA, nsims)

for (j in 1:nsims) {
    x = rpois(N_true, lam_true)
    x_obs = x[x > 0]
    m = length(x_obs)
    
    negloglik = function(lam) {
        -1 * (sum(x_obs) * log(lam) - m * 
            lam - m * log(1 - exp(-lam)))
    }
    
    obj = nlm(negloglik, 0.5, stepmax = 0.1)
    lam_hat = obj$estimate
    N_hats[j] = m/(1 - exp(-lam_hat))
}
hist(N_hats, xlim = c(0, 2 * N_true))
abline(v = N_true)

mean(N_hats)
## [1] 1003.831
sd(N_hats)
## [1] 58.47023
# 95% confidence interval for N
mean(N_hats) + c(-1, 1) * 2.96 * sd(N_hats)
## [1]  830.7594 1176.9032
